 Age boldly considers how to frame the human condition in troubled times. As we open ourselves to the implications of the Anthropocene, few writers are as likely as Chakrabarty to shape our understanding of the best way forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCivilization, Modern. 0aClimatic changesxPolitical aspects. 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspects. 0aGlobalization. 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aHuman ecology. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aclimate change, history, modernity, globalization, society, anthropocene, ecology, sustainability, habitability, humanism, geology, markets, capitalism, geography, weather, earth science, rivers, biodiversity, wildfires, drought, technology, planet, ocean, acidification, population, industrialization, kant, labor, environment, environmentalism, conservation, preservation, irrigation, water rights, inequality, poverty, geoengineering, heidegger, fossil fuel, energy, ethics, colonialism, nonfiction, biology, zoology, politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226733050423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226733050/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles